To achieve this, you can simply use the [JavaScript DOM API](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Document_Object_Model/Introduction#What_is_the_DOM.3F) to dynamically create an `&lt;img /&gt;` HTML element whilst specifying the URL, the width, height, etc. 

For instance, you could create a reusable function for showing images like such:
```javascript
const displayImg = (url, width, height, id, className) =&gt; {
  const img = document.createElement(&#39;img&#39;);

  img.src = url;
  img.width = width;
  img.height = height;
  img.id = id;
  img.className = className;

  document.body.appendChild(img);
}
```

Calling the function above will create an image based on the arguments provided and will append it within the `&lt;body&gt;` tag.

